Many questions are raised about friendship—first, on the line of those who take in wider considerations and extend the term. For some hold that like is friend to like, whence the sayings:
Mark how God ever brings like men together Hom. Od. 17.218 ;
For jackdaw by the side of jackdaw . . .; Birds of a feather flock together. Sc. ἱζάνει, perches : an iambic verse quoted in full Aristot. Gtr. Mor. 1208b 9, and in the form κολοιὸν ποτὶ κολοιόν Aristot. Nic. Eth. 1155a 35, where the dialect suggests that it is from a Doric poet (unknown). And thief knows thief and wolf his fellow wolf.set a thief to catch a thief. The origin of the verse is unknown.
